### Describe the feature you'd like to request

In webpack, hot module replacement exposes an [accept API](https://webpack.js.org/api/hot-module-replacement/#accept) which allows you to control how your updated dependencies are processed. This feature, for some reason, is not exposed to server-side modules in next.js.

One common reason to implement this behavior is to copy a cache from an old version of the code to a new version. This feature is particularly useful when combined with `require.context` and wildcard imports. For example, consider a module that is very expensive to initialize. In this example, we load Markdown files using `raw-loader` and process them. When a Markdown file changes, only the changed file will be processed, because the cache is not thrown away.

```typescript
import { Post } from "./index";

function loadPost(filename: string, data: string): Promise<Post> {
  // Process markdown, render, etc.
}

const _postContext = require.context("raw-loader!../../_posts/", true, /\.md$/);

const db: Record<string, { data: string; post: Promise<Post> }> = {};

async function loadPost(filename: string, data: string): Promise<Post> {
  let record = db[filename];
  if (record?.data !== data) {
    record = { data: data, post: loadPost(filename, data) };
    db[filename] = record;
  }
  return record.post;
}

export function loadPosts(): Promise<Post[]> {
  return Promise.all(
    _postContext.keys().map((k) => Post.load(k, _postContext(k).default))
  );
}

module.hot.accept(_postContext.keys());
```

### Describe the solution you'd like

This feature is built in to webpack, so I'd like to see it enabled for next.js server code.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

Not supporting this means that the expensive initialization function needs to be called for all modules whenever any module changes. In the toy example, all posts are reparsed whenever any post changes, wasting time.

